00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:08.790
So, let's go through these individually.

00:08:08.800 --> 00:08:10.800
First of all, planning.

00:08:10.800 --> 00:08:14.810
This is about deciding what to
make and whom to make it for.

00:08:17.810 --> 00:08:21.990
There's about four or five steps here,
and this is not the all-encompassing

00:08:21.990 --> 00:08:25.240
list of what you need to do
for planning your software.

00:08:25.240 --> 00:08:27.850
This is, based on my experience
working with developers,

00:08:27.850 --> 00:08:31.520
these are the areas that most developers,
I think, don't spend enough time on.

00:08:34.190 --> 00:08:35.980
So the first thing that's critical,
I think,

00:08:36.040 --> 00:08:37.790
is understanding who your users are.

00:08:37.800 --> 00:08:41.160
First of all, first and foremost,
you're not your user.

00:08:41.160 --> 00:08:43.500
You might come from the
experience of your users.

00:08:43.500 --> 00:08:46.480
You might have been a teacher
previously in your previous life,

00:08:46.540 --> 00:08:49.420
and now you're a software
developer for K through 12,

00:08:49.420 --> 00:08:53.350
or you might have been an accountant,
but now you're writing software for

00:08:53.350 --> 00:08:55.280
personal finance or what have you.

00:08:55.280 --> 00:08:57.610
So you might have some
sense of who your user is,

00:08:57.620 --> 00:08:58.930
but you are no longer your user.

00:08:58.940 --> 00:09:02.020
You're the developer,
and you have business pressures,

00:09:02.240 --> 00:09:04.300
and you've got all kinds
of things that are going to

00:09:04.390 --> 00:09:06.990
influence the decisions you make.

00:09:07.390 --> 00:09:10.500
It's important for you to understand who
your users are and what their needs are,

00:09:10.500 --> 00:09:14.530
what their priorities are,
what their expertise is.

00:09:15.790 --> 00:09:18.330
And understanding,
based upon their expertise,

00:09:18.340 --> 00:09:21.820
that some users who aren't that
sophisticated are going to become

00:09:21.820 --> 00:09:25.020
proficient in certain tasks,
and your software needs to lead

00:09:25.030 --> 00:09:28.270
them towards that proficiency,
and they're going to graduate

00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:30.100
to more complex tasks as well.

00:09:30.100 --> 00:09:34.570
But highly sophisticated users on
the computer with your software are

00:09:34.670 --> 00:09:38.090
going to be masters at some tasks,
novices at others,

00:09:38.090 --> 00:09:42.900
and are going to be frustrated mostly
when your product gets in the way.

00:09:44.260 --> 00:09:45.990
Well, this seems like common sense,
right?

00:09:45.990 --> 00:09:48.960
Truth of the matter is,
I think most software developers

00:09:49.160 --> 00:09:52.610
are trying to aim for whoever
the heck will buy their product.

00:09:52.680 --> 00:09:54.920
It's like, okay,
let's just throw everything into this

00:09:55.050 --> 00:09:57.170
puppy and hope that anybody in the world,
you know,

00:09:57.170 --> 00:10:00.330
whoever can buy it will buy it because
it's just another customer for us.

00:10:00.330 --> 00:10:03.680
But the truth is,
I think some of the best products on the

00:10:03.680 --> 00:10:08.200
platform are the ones that are focused,
very focused on a particular market

00:10:08.200 --> 00:10:10.900
segment and at a particular set of users.

00:10:10.900 --> 00:10:11.820
And they address the
needs of those users,

00:10:11.820 --> 00:10:13.740
and they address the
needs of those users.

00:10:13.760 --> 00:10:17.380
perfectly and those products
totally dominate that space.

00:10:17.380 --> 00:10:20.330
And think for a minute of some
of the software that you use

00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:21.470
that fits into that space.

00:10:21.470 --> 00:10:23.390
I mean,
I think all of us could probably identify

00:10:23.390 --> 00:10:24.730
a product or two that fits into that.

00:10:24.730 --> 00:10:29.710
So it's critical, I think,
to pick your audience and know what

00:10:29.710 --> 00:10:34.520
their needs are and pay attention
to how sophisticated they are.

00:10:34.520 --> 00:10:38.980
And a great example of this, for example,
is if you were going for

00:10:38.980 --> 00:10:42.820
less sophisticated users and
producing an iMovie type product.

00:10:42.820 --> 00:10:45.960
I mean, right from the get-go,
Apple said, you know what,

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:47.340
iMovie is for home users.

00:10:47.340 --> 00:10:49.360
They're infrequently on the computer.

00:10:49.570 --> 00:10:52.970
They're going to be bothered
or hindered in some way by the

00:10:52.970 --> 00:10:55.980
multi-windowing environment of Mac OS X.

00:10:55.980 --> 00:10:58.460
We'll just give them a full
screen experience because

00:10:58.460 --> 00:11:02.040
they're totally focused on
that exercise of editing video.

00:11:02.040 --> 00:11:05.880
That was a very deliberate decision
on our part to create a product

00:11:06.470 --> 00:11:07.750
for less sophisticated users.

00:11:07.760 --> 00:11:11.720
Clearly, the experience with
Final Cut Pro is different than

00:11:11.830 --> 00:11:13.690
the experience with iMovie,
right?

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:17.140
So there's two examples of
how the product design was

00:11:17.530 --> 00:11:20.980
influenced by the user base,
and that's kind of the point

00:11:20.980 --> 00:11:21.780
I want to make for you guys.

00:11:21.820 --> 00:11:24.630
So the first step in planning
was understanding your users.

00:11:24.790 --> 00:11:27.240
The second one is sort of
knowing your application.

00:11:27.360 --> 00:11:29.110
Understand your application.

00:11:29.110 --> 00:11:32.270
Understand what it is that
you really want your app to do

00:11:32.270 --> 00:11:34.140
and get a good grasp of that.

00:11:34.180 --> 00:11:38.120
And I think as you come to define what
it is you want your application to do,

00:11:38.190 --> 00:11:40.570
you need to take into account
the fact that you have a lot

00:11:40.570 --> 00:11:41.440
of experience with the app.

00:11:41.440 --> 00:11:44.320
You, your company, you as an individual,
you, your company,

00:11:44.320 --> 00:11:47.800
have certain value add that you can
bring to the market with your product.

00:11:47.810 --> 00:11:49.760
You have certain expertise.

00:11:49.760 --> 00:11:54.550
You have certain inherent strengths as
a company or inherent sort of assets

00:11:54.680 --> 00:11:56.350
that you can bring to the product.

00:11:56.550 --> 00:12:00.300
And your product should be
built around those primarily.

00:12:01.040 --> 00:12:03.880
It's important to design for usability,
understand what the

00:12:03.880 --> 00:12:04.960
workflow is of the users.

00:12:05.040 --> 00:12:07.910
How do users expect to
work with this product,

00:12:07.910 --> 00:12:11.490
and how can we make the
product map to that experience?

00:12:12.180 --> 00:12:15.320
Think about the interaction
with other applications.

00:12:15.350 --> 00:12:18.210
If your application is aimed
for less sophisticated users and

00:12:18.210 --> 00:12:21.140
you're a single window product
like iMovie was originally,

00:12:21.140 --> 00:12:24.310
it's unlikely that the user's
going to be interacting with other

00:12:24.430 --> 00:12:26.220
applications at the same time.

00:12:26.220 --> 00:12:27.440
They're editing movies.

00:12:27.440 --> 00:12:29.170
They're not doing drag and drop.

00:12:29.490 --> 00:12:32.320
They might do cut and paste, perhaps,
but not likely.

00:12:32.320 --> 00:12:35.360
And so within the application,
they might do cut and paste,

00:12:35.420 --> 00:12:38.860
but not any data exchange with
other applications in that sense.

00:12:40.860 --> 00:12:45.130
Interaction with other applications
is important to think about as you

00:12:45.140 --> 00:12:46.880
consider who your user base is.

00:12:46.880 --> 00:12:49.330
And all of these things,
in terms of planning,

00:12:49.810 --> 00:12:54.460
help you to craft what your product will
be and what its feature set will be.

