00:12:57.360 --> 00:13:00.200
you know, most people are trying to
do everything for everybody.

00:13:00.200 --> 00:13:03.860
And so then they're demoing the
product for me as I do a UI review

00:13:03.940 --> 00:13:06.260
and they're showing off how,
you know,

00:13:06.260 --> 00:13:09.570
the app can do this and it can export
and import and drag and drop and,

00:13:09.570 --> 00:13:11.840
you know, it can stand on its head
and it does all this stuff.

00:13:11.920 --> 00:13:15.870
And I keep coming back to them saying,
well, who's using this product?

00:13:15.880 --> 00:13:18.980
Well, you know,
we've got some customers here and say,

00:13:19.080 --> 00:13:21.070
well, you know, who's using this?

00:13:21.200 --> 00:13:21.900
What are their needs?

00:13:21.940 --> 00:13:26.600
And as I keep driving on that point,
developers realize, you know what?

00:13:26.740 --> 00:13:28.610
Actually, we don't need that.

00:13:28.700 --> 00:13:30.120
We could drop that whole feature.

00:13:30.120 --> 00:13:31.080
No one would care.

00:13:31.080 --> 00:13:34.060
And the usability of the
product might increase.

00:13:34.060 --> 00:13:36.040
So I don't want to belabor the point.

00:13:36.040 --> 00:13:37.380
I've got tons of stuff
to go through today.

00:13:37.380 --> 00:13:38.070
So let me move on.

00:13:38.080 --> 00:13:39.270
All right.

00:13:39.740 --> 00:13:41.610
Deliver solutions and not features.

00:13:41.610 --> 00:13:44.530
I hammer on this every year at WC,
and I think we're getting

00:13:44.760 --> 00:13:46.970
better in this as a community,
as a platform,

00:13:46.970 --> 00:13:48.980
we're getting better in this regard.

00:13:48.980 --> 00:13:52.140
But still, and there's some examples
I'll show you later on,

00:13:52.140 --> 00:13:55.790
still there's this tendency to just
pack in the features because there's

00:13:55.860 --> 00:13:59.820
pressure from your marketing team or
whoever it is that's giving you pressure

00:13:59.820 --> 00:14:03.330
as an engineer to get those checkboxes
on the side of the product box,

00:14:03.500 --> 00:14:03.680
right?

00:14:03.810 --> 00:14:05.830
It's not about features for the user.

00:14:05.830 --> 00:14:09.580
It's about whether the product
delivers on the promise.

00:14:09.600 --> 00:14:10.590
It's about what it can do.

00:14:10.590 --> 00:14:14.880
So you need to be producing products that
deliver an end solution for customers

00:14:14.880 --> 00:14:17.220
that is the be-all and end-all for them.

00:14:20.160 --> 00:14:22.470
Use the 80% solution.

00:14:22.480 --> 00:14:25.800
This is really all about designing
for 80% of your customers.

00:14:25.800 --> 00:14:29.840
Once you identify who your users are,
then you can sort of aim for trying

00:14:29.840 --> 00:14:34.770
to please 80% of those well-defined,
for that well-defined audience.

00:14:34.820 --> 00:14:39.120
A lot of people spend most of their time
developing for 20% of their audience,

00:14:39.120 --> 00:14:41.100
who tend to be the vocal minority.

00:14:41.100 --> 00:14:44.320
It's the people who tend to be a
little bit more sophisticated who can

00:14:44.320 --> 00:14:47.670
get that feedback into the developer
through a blog or through an email

00:14:47.670 --> 00:14:49.400
or whatever mechanism there is.

00:14:49.460 --> 00:14:52.020
The less sophisticated users kind of go,
"Well, you know,

00:14:52.020 --> 00:14:54.000
I'm not sure how to get the
feedback to the developer,"

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.900
so they're kind of silent.

00:14:57.230 --> 00:15:00.420
They're the ones you kind
of want to design for rather

00:15:00.460 --> 00:15:03.270
than the vocal minority,
so keep that in mind.

00:15:03.320 --> 00:15:06.370
Don't always design
for the vocal minority.

00:15:06.890 --> 00:15:08.920
The best tools are the ones you're
not even aware you're using,

00:15:09.110 --> 00:15:09.280
right?

00:15:09.280 --> 00:15:11.540
If you think of a carpenter
or a mechanic or any of the

00:15:11.540 --> 00:15:14.500
tradespeople out there in the world,
they have whole vast

00:15:14.570 --> 00:15:16.100
collections of tools.

00:15:16.100 --> 00:15:16.800
Why?

00:15:16.800 --> 00:15:19.440
Because every one of those
tools is properly balanced,

00:15:19.440 --> 00:15:22.510
it's tuned exactly for what it does,
and I think it's no different

00:15:22.510 --> 00:15:24.020
in the software industry.

00:15:24.480 --> 00:15:27.770
I think I would much rather have
a computer with hundreds of apps,

00:15:27.770 --> 00:15:30.160
all that are tuned for what
they're supposed to do,

00:15:30.160 --> 00:15:32.810
all that are scriptable so I can
use something like Automator to

00:15:32.810 --> 00:15:35.760
start connecting them together
and create a great workflow,

00:15:35.760 --> 00:15:38.140
than having three apps that are just,
you know,

00:15:38.230 --> 00:15:41.430
got thousands of features in them
that I can't even find half of,

00:15:41.510 --> 00:15:42.960
half of the features for.

00:15:42.960 --> 00:15:44.140
All right.

00:15:45.770 --> 00:15:47.850
Third thing to do in terms
of planning your product is

00:15:47.860 --> 00:15:49.210
understanding your market needs.

00:15:49.210 --> 00:15:53.050
If you think about the characteristics,
for a moment,

00:15:53.220 --> 00:15:57.160
of some of the best software
you've used on the platform,

00:15:57.490 --> 00:15:59.420
what would you come up with?

00:16:01.760 --> 00:16:03.970
Some of the characteristics of the
software and the best platform,

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.600
I think,
are the ones down here on the left.

00:16:06.730 --> 00:16:09.880
Some of the best software I've
ever used was high performance,

00:16:09.930 --> 00:16:11.360
very responsive.

00:16:11.440 --> 00:16:12.600
It was elegant.

00:16:12.670 --> 00:16:13.790
It was attractive.

00:16:14.120 --> 00:16:15.460
It was dead easy to use.

00:16:15.460 --> 00:16:18.180
I got into the thing and I was
able to do what I wanted to do.

00:16:18.180 --> 00:16:19.380
It was compatible.

00:16:19.380 --> 00:16:24.230
As I started using it, I realized, hey,
I need this image from over here,

00:16:24.230 --> 00:16:27.970
this whatchamacallit from
some such other application.

00:16:28.040 --> 00:16:29.110
And boom, I could get it in there,
no problem.

00:16:29.400 --> 00:16:30.660
Very mobile, right?

00:16:30.660 --> 00:16:33.720
Launches quickly in my PowerBook,
has no issues going to sleep.

00:16:33.720 --> 00:16:35.530
It's just a really mobile application.

00:16:35.580 --> 00:16:36.700
It's accessible.

00:16:36.700 --> 00:16:38.800
We'll talk about that a little bit more.

00:16:38.800 --> 00:16:41.600
I think these are some of the
characteristics that we all want

00:16:41.690 --> 00:16:44.320
in the products that we use,
whether they're the ones we write

00:16:44.410 --> 00:16:45.670
or whether they're the ones we use.

00:16:45.740 --> 00:16:50.410
So if we look at some of those
characteristics and then contrast

00:16:50.410 --> 00:16:55.660
them with some of the market segments
that many of you are participating in,

00:16:55.660 --> 00:16:59.280
and certainly Apple is participating in,
it's interesting how some of

00:16:59.280 --> 00:17:00.990
them map to those market needs.

00:17:01.040 --> 00:17:07.260
This isn't meant to be the definitive
statement of where Apple's participating,

00:17:07.260 --> 00:17:08.780
doing business.

00:17:08.780 --> 00:17:10.930
This isn't meant to be the
definitive statement of what

00:17:10.930 --> 00:17:12.420
the characteristics are for any.

00:17:12.420 --> 00:17:17.560
Again,
it's John's perspective on this point,

00:17:17.560 --> 00:17:21.160
and I think the whole point here is
just to get you to think about what

00:17:21.320 --> 00:17:23.870
are the characteristics that you
want in your application and how

00:17:23.960 --> 00:17:26.540
do those map to the market segment
in which you're participating.

00:17:27.660 --> 00:17:30.760
As you understand who your user is,
you're going to identify them and

00:17:30.760 --> 00:17:32.280
place them within a market segment.

00:17:32.280 --> 00:17:34.890
So let's just take the first two columns.

00:17:34.900 --> 00:17:37.620
If you're developing a
game for the platform,

00:17:37.620 --> 00:17:41.840
what are likely to be the highest
priority characteristics for you

00:17:41.840 --> 00:17:43.410
that you have within your product?

00:17:43.510 --> 00:17:45.730
Well, high performance is key for games,
right?

00:17:45.840 --> 00:17:49.200
Great responsiveness,
great fast rendering of stuff on screen,

00:17:49.200 --> 00:17:51.250
attractiveness.

00:17:51.320 --> 00:17:55.600
A lot of the sex appeal of games
is how cool they look and what the

00:17:55.670 --> 00:17:57.380
audio is like and how attractive.

00:17:57.380 --> 00:17:57.520
The game is a game of games.

00:17:57.520 --> 00:17:58.400
That's what the whole experience is.

00:17:58.500 --> 00:18:01.660
And easy to use, I think,
is important for games, too.

00:18:01.660 --> 00:18:04.110
If it's too hard to play, it's like,
well, forget this.

00:18:06.030 --> 00:18:09.500
Contrast that with the home user,
with the home market, you know,

00:18:09.500 --> 00:18:11.940
high performance isn't
as big a deal for them.

00:18:11.940 --> 00:18:14.680
In fact, I chose not to put it on the
slide as an option for them.

00:18:14.680 --> 00:18:18.010
I would say for home users,
for the home market, infrequent,

00:18:18.010 --> 00:18:21.730
less sophisticated users typically,
elegance, attractiveness,

00:18:21.730 --> 00:18:23.240
and ease of use are key.

00:18:23.240 --> 00:18:26.590
Once you identify which
characteristics you want to go after,

00:18:26.590 --> 00:18:28.690
it's important to prioritize them.

00:18:31.090 --> 00:18:32.210
So take those same markets.

00:18:32.210 --> 00:18:33.520
Again, this is John's opinion.

00:18:33.520 --> 00:18:35.160
This is not meant to be the authority.

00:18:35.160 --> 00:18:39.060
But I would say for games,
number one is performance.

00:18:39.060 --> 00:18:41.530
So if you're writing a game
and you haven't run some of the

00:18:41.540 --> 00:18:44.420
performance analysis tools and
tuned that product for Mac OS X,

00:18:44.420 --> 00:18:47.590
I think you're missing the boat in
terms of your opportunity to stand out

00:18:47.680 --> 00:18:51.620
and distinguish your application on the
platform relative to your competition.

00:18:52.800 --> 00:18:53.920
Responsiveness is, again, key.

00:18:53.920 --> 00:18:54.930
I think the two go together.

00:18:54.930 --> 00:18:55.910
And attractiveness.

00:18:55.910 --> 00:18:59.330
Home users, I think the number one thing
for most users who are less

00:18:59.330 --> 00:19:01.010
sophisticated is ease of use.

00:19:01.020 --> 00:19:03.790
If you don't get that right,
your product, I think,

00:19:03.880 --> 00:19:06.660
isn't going to be nearly as
successful as it could be.

00:19:06.680 --> 00:19:07.960
All right.

00:19:08.130 --> 00:19:11.980
So once you've done all those things,
you sort of throw it all into the pot,

00:19:11.980 --> 00:19:14.940
you stir up the soup,
and I think out of that comes a great

00:19:15.290 --> 00:19:19.100
starting point and a great understanding
for what your product can be.

00:19:19.100 --> 00:19:21.930
And then it's from there that you go on
to your development plans and you sort

00:19:21.930 --> 00:19:22.760
of figure out what you're thinking about.

00:19:22.820 --> 00:19:24.880
What your feature set will be
and how are you going to end

00:19:24.880 --> 00:19:27.290
up delivering the solution that
you think that market needs.

00:19:27.440 --> 00:19:30.210
And again, you know,
I touched on this a little bit before,

00:19:30.230 --> 00:19:33.310
avoid the market buckshot approach,
buckshot market approach,

00:19:33.310 --> 00:19:35.950
which is kind of like stick
the product in a gun and shoot,

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.510
you know, and hope it hits as
many users as possible.

00:19:38.700 --> 00:19:40.310
It doesn't work, I don't think.

00:19:40.360 --> 00:19:43.990
And most of the developers I've met with
agree that if you focus the product,

00:19:43.990 --> 00:19:47.240
you're going to get a great,
great experience and great business.

00:19:47.520 --> 00:19:49.130
So that's planning, step one.

00:19:49.340 --> 00:19:54.870
The second thing is creating a first...
Creating a great first impression.

00:19:54.880 --> 00:19:57.510
This is all about surprising and
delighting users from the start.

00:19:57.570 --> 00:19:59.710
Remember,
you go to this restaurant and you get

00:19:59.820 --> 00:20:03.540
this great aroma and the music is great
and you think the people you're with are

00:20:03.570 --> 00:20:05.990
great and the whole thing is awesome.

00:20:06.040 --> 00:20:08.310
I think that is true
for software as well.

00:20:08.320 --> 00:20:13.760
And I've reviewed tons of software in
the years at Apple and I'll tell you,

00:20:13.760 --> 00:20:16.780
some get this right and some do not.

00:20:18.440 --> 00:20:20.000
I think first of all it
starts with packaging.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:22.600
What is your physical packaging
like if you're in a retail store?

00:20:22.600 --> 00:20:25.160
Clearly some of you might be
developing for enterprise or

00:20:25.160 --> 00:20:26.620
for in-house or for schools.

00:20:26.620 --> 00:20:28.790
There may not be a real package,
so that's fine.

00:20:28.930 --> 00:20:29.720
Just ignore this.

00:20:29.900 --> 00:20:33.670
But for those of you in a retail store,
I think packaging is a big deal.

00:20:33.680 --> 00:20:36.890
If you're not communicating the
system requirements in the package,

00:20:37.020 --> 00:20:39.330
you're setting yourself up
for a tech support call,

00:20:39.330 --> 00:20:42.010
which costs money because a
user's going to call in and say,

00:20:42.250 --> 00:20:44.850
hey, I bought this product and it
doesn't run on my machine.

00:20:44.960 --> 00:20:47.960
So make sure that system
requirements are really clear.

00:20:48.450 --> 00:20:51.990
If it runs on Mac OS X,
put the badge on it.

00:20:52.830 --> 00:20:53.500
Distribution.

00:20:53.570 --> 00:20:56.040
A lot of software goes in retail stores.

00:20:56.040 --> 00:20:56.770
It's on a CD.

00:20:56.770 --> 00:20:57.530
It's in a box.

00:20:57.650 --> 00:21:00.720
But equally, there's a lot of you selling
software directly on the Internet,

00:21:00.720 --> 00:21:01.540
and that's great.

00:21:02.040 --> 00:21:05.590
Disk images are the way to go.

00:21:05.590 --> 00:21:07.070
Put your software in a disk image.

00:21:07.120 --> 00:21:08.100
It's already compressed.

00:21:08.140 --> 00:21:10.500
You can put a password on
it if that's important.

00:21:12.160 --> 00:21:14.740
But avoid compressing the compressed.

00:21:14.740 --> 00:21:22.800
I have seen some really, really awful,
really scary situations where I've got,

00:21:22.800 --> 00:21:25.460
you know,
I get a CD or I download something,

00:21:25.460 --> 00:21:29.020
and there's stuff inside, you know,
there's a stuff inside an HQX,

00:21:29.100 --> 00:21:32.560
inside of a DMG, inside of a... I don't
know how that happens,

00:21:32.560 --> 00:21:34.940
but it just does, and it's something that
we should all avoid.

00:21:36.960 --> 00:21:40.740
Installation is a great way to
create a great first impression.

00:21:40.770 --> 00:21:43.140
Make it dead easy.

00:21:43.190 --> 00:21:45.230
Users buy the product, they spent money,
they want to get this

00:21:45.230 --> 00:21:49.860
thing up and running,
they probably have a real need

00:21:49.880 --> 00:21:56.730
that they want to satisfy,
and if your product is a pain to install,

00:21:56.730 --> 00:21:56.730
it's going to just knock down
their impression of the product.

00:21:57.010 --> 00:21:57.980
Drag installs are great.

00:21:57.980 --> 00:22:00.110
Disk images support drag installs.

00:22:00.200 --> 00:22:03.640
The thing mounts and you drag your
icon over to the applications folder.

00:22:03.640 --> 00:22:05.780
The user can put it wherever they want,
which I think is really

00:22:05.880 --> 00:22:06.690
critical for installs.

00:22:06.820 --> 00:22:09.850
Disk images,
I don't know if you knew this,

00:22:09.860 --> 00:22:12.960
but disk images allow you to display a
software license agreement or a EULA.

00:22:12.960 --> 00:22:15.060
It's a little bit hokey
getting it to work,

00:22:15.160 --> 00:22:16.560
but you can make it happen.

00:22:16.560 --> 00:22:19.010
And so if that's the only reason
you're using an installer,

00:22:19.120 --> 00:22:21.460
so you can display some sort
of legal license agreement,

00:22:21.460 --> 00:22:24.910
you can actually get away from installer,
go to a disk image, and put that license

00:22:24.910 --> 00:22:26.330
agreement in the disk image.

00:22:28.910 --> 00:22:30.920
or go with the
Mac OS X package installer.

00:22:30.920 --> 00:22:33.640
So there's a session later on today,
I think, about using the installer.

00:22:33.640 --> 00:22:37.480
I think it's important to avoid
shutting down other processes.

00:22:37.480 --> 00:22:41.600
Recently, I installed some software
for the Apple Design Awards,

00:22:41.610 --> 00:22:45.430
and the blasted installer forced
me to shut down everything

00:22:45.490 --> 00:22:48.150
that was running on my machine,
my browser, my mail, everything,

00:22:48.150 --> 00:22:49.880
just so it could install the software.

00:22:49.880 --> 00:22:52.750
I'm not sure why,
and it was a total pain.

00:22:52.760 --> 00:22:55.900
Avoid unnecessary authentication.

00:22:55.900 --> 00:22:58.820
If you're not installing outside of
the current logged-in user's domain

00:22:58.820 --> 00:23:02.160
and just put stuff on that inside
their home directory or what have you,

00:23:02.160 --> 00:23:04.560
there's no need for authentication,
so don't ask me to authenticate.

00:23:04.560 --> 00:23:05.570
It's a bother.

00:23:05.580 --> 00:23:07.520
And avoid custom installers.

00:23:07.620 --> 00:23:08.500
Don't write your own thing.

00:23:08.500 --> 00:23:11.900
Just use what's available today on
Mac OS X or from some third parties.

00:23:11.900 --> 00:23:14.260
There's some good software
installers that are available.

00:23:14.260 --> 00:23:18.340
And the other thing is
consider first-time launch

00:23:19.020 --> 00:23:21.300
initialization or configuration.

00:23:21.300 --> 00:23:24.080
So allow for a drag install,
but then the first time

00:23:24.080 --> 00:23:26.510
your app is launched,
build in sort of your own

00:23:26.510 --> 00:23:29.720
custom installer at that point,
but don't make it look like an installer.

00:23:29.720 --> 00:23:34.520
Just sort of display an alert that says,
one moment, please, while we get set up.

00:23:34.610 --> 00:23:37.280
Or if you're a game for kids, say,
one moment, please,

00:23:37.340 --> 00:23:41.000
while Mickey Mouse gets ready to
play with you or what have you.

00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:42.980
And in the background,
you're installing some stuff.

00:23:43.040 --> 00:23:48.290
So I have four little girls,
and there's no more frustrating thing

00:23:48.290 --> 00:23:51.300
for me than when my wife calls and says,
we got this CD from you that you

00:23:51.300 --> 00:23:52.880
brought home from work to try.

00:23:52.880 --> 00:23:54.640
And she says, we can't install it.

00:23:54.660 --> 00:23:56.160
And my nine-year-old calls.

00:23:56.160 --> 00:23:58.900
And there's multiple installers.

00:23:58.960 --> 00:23:59.680
It's a total pain.

00:23:59.680 --> 00:24:01.700
And I think this is a great way to
create a great first impression.

00:24:01.740 --> 00:24:02.900
So I don't want to belabor the point.

00:24:02.900 --> 00:24:06.900
Now, I was going to do an install,
a lousy install demo.

00:24:06.900 --> 00:24:10.420
And I decided not to in the end because
to save the face of the developer.

00:24:10.420 --> 00:24:14.140
But I'm going to tell you about it
so that there's no logos displayed.

00:24:14.140 --> 00:24:19.510
This is an app that is an
installer from a very well-known

00:24:19.520 --> 00:24:22.440
manufacturer of printers.

00:24:22.440 --> 00:24:24.090
And it is.

00:24:24.280 --> 00:24:25.260
It's actually for a scanner.

00:24:25.260 --> 00:24:30.020
And so you download this disk image,
and you run this thing,

00:24:30.020 --> 00:24:32.160
and it mounts on the desktop,
and there's a single icon.

00:24:32.160 --> 00:24:33.030
And you think, okay, great.

00:24:33.200 --> 00:24:34.860
But it's clearly not a drag install.

00:24:34.860 --> 00:24:36.820
It's got a crummy icon.

00:24:36.820 --> 00:24:38.280
It looks like Mac OS 9.

00:24:38.280 --> 00:24:40.780
And you double-click this thing,
and you get a license agreement.

