00:26:35.440 --> 00:26:36.170
The fundamentals.

00:26:36.170 --> 00:26:39.710
This is all about the essential
elements that your product should have.

00:26:39.770 --> 00:26:41.830
And I think pretty much
every product in Mac OS X,

00:26:41.830 --> 00:26:44.470
if you're shipping to end users
and you're an application,

00:26:44.580 --> 00:26:47.440
this is a big section that
I'm going to talk about here.

00:26:47.440 --> 00:26:48.120
But you know what?

00:26:48.200 --> 00:26:50.140
This is the stuff that your
app needs to be leveraging.

00:26:50.140 --> 00:26:53.370
If it's not, you're going to be totally,
you're going to be,

00:26:53.370 --> 00:26:57.560
somebody else is going to stand above
you in terms of the competitive space.

00:26:57.560 --> 00:27:00.270
Your competitor is going to come out
and adopt some of these technologies,

00:27:00.330 --> 00:27:03.120
and I think they're going to stand head
and shoulders above you as a result.

00:27:03.700 --> 00:27:07.230
So, understanding what the essentials
are means that you need to understand

00:27:07.340 --> 00:27:10.250
what the Mac OS X environment is
and what it brings to the table.

00:27:10.250 --> 00:27:13.390
Mac OS X environment
has a single menu bar.

00:27:13.390 --> 00:27:14.370
There's just one.

00:27:14.370 --> 00:27:16.720
So don't stick other
ones inside of windows.

00:27:16.720 --> 00:27:20.830
It's a layered multi-windowing system.

00:27:20.830 --> 00:27:22.950
MDI doesn't cut it.

00:27:23.200 --> 00:27:25.980
We don't want child windows
inside of a single parent window.

00:27:25.980 --> 00:27:27.510
That's what the desktop is, right?

00:27:27.530 --> 00:27:30.130
We want multiple windows that
we can minimize to the dock.

00:27:30.270 --> 00:27:32.310
Don't create some other
dock inside of a window,

00:27:32.320 --> 00:27:33.880
you know, the MDI experience.

00:27:33.900 --> 00:27:35.120
That just doesn't cut it.

00:27:35.290 --> 00:27:37.040
So if your app's
shipping on the platform,

00:27:37.160 --> 00:27:39.270
this is a basic that
you've got to adhere to.

00:27:39.790 --> 00:27:41.630
Another reality of Mac OS X is the dock.

00:27:41.770 --> 00:27:42.710
The dock is there.

00:27:42.710 --> 00:27:43.740
It's just there.

00:27:43.740 --> 00:27:46.650
Users can move it around the screen,
but it's a reality, and it is there,

00:27:46.710 --> 00:27:49.150
and your application needs
to respect where the dock is,

00:27:49.620 --> 00:27:52.440
because there's nothing more
frustrating than unplugging your

00:27:52.440 --> 00:27:56.640
PowerBook from a large display at work,
going on a trip, opening up your display,

00:27:56.640 --> 00:27:59.640
and suddenly now this app window
is hidden behind the dock,

00:27:59.640 --> 00:28:03.300
and you can't resize it, and, you know,
little things like that.

00:28:03.390 --> 00:28:06.180
So respect the dock's position
and size your windows accordingly.

00:28:06.380 --> 00:28:09.620
And there's some standard behaviors
for when your app icon is clicked.

00:28:09.640 --> 00:28:30.680
Mac OS X is an always-on environment.

00:28:31.770 --> 00:28:35.710
Don't rely on rebooting to clear out
caches or clear out temporary files.

00:28:35.820 --> 00:28:38.120
It's an always-on environment.

00:28:38.120 --> 00:28:39.570
My PowerBook stays live.

00:28:39.580 --> 00:28:44.180
I think I probably reboot
every couple of days for,

00:28:44.180 --> 00:28:46.810
well, I'll tell you why in a
moment on my next slide.

00:28:46.820 --> 00:28:48.460
But there's a reason why I reboot.

00:28:48.460 --> 00:28:49.000
But you know what?

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:51.780
If I didn't have it for that situation,
I probably would leave my PowerBook on

00:28:51.780 --> 00:28:53.580
for days and not have to restart.

00:28:53.580 --> 00:28:55.400
It's always sleep, wake, sleep, wake,
sleep, wake.

00:28:55.430 --> 00:28:56.760
The system is always on.

00:28:56.780 --> 00:29:00.930
Don't rely on login items to be the
way that stuff's going to start up.

00:29:01.040 --> 00:29:04.700
If users cancel a process somehow,
and you're relying on login

00:29:04.700 --> 00:29:07.470
to start that thing up,
and there's no other way for the

00:29:07.480 --> 00:29:10.130
user to start up that process,
I think you're in trouble.

00:29:10.140 --> 00:29:13.090
Well, actually, the user's in trouble,
and they may not know

00:29:13.090 --> 00:29:14.890
to get you in trouble,
but...

00:29:15.360 --> 00:29:17.010
Another thing about
Mac OS X's environment is

00:29:17.010 --> 00:29:18.220
that it's highly adaptable.

00:29:18.220 --> 00:29:22.850
The beautiful thing about Mac OS X is
it adapts to all kinds of changes.

00:29:22.860 --> 00:29:25.620
I take my PowerBook on my
bike to work every day,

00:29:25.860 --> 00:29:27.710
and I plug it into a
cinema display on my desk,

00:29:27.850 --> 00:29:31.820
I plug it into the Ethernet network,
and I often unplug it throughout the day,

00:29:31.820 --> 00:29:33.480
probably 16, 18 times.

00:29:33.480 --> 00:29:36.020
I'm going in and out of my office,
plugging this thing in, unplugging it,

00:29:36.330 --> 00:29:39.070
going to meetings,
unplugging from the wired hard LAN,

00:29:39.070 --> 00:29:42.000
you know, the Ethernet,
and going on to airport.

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:44.860
So I'm detaching and attaching displays.

00:29:45.140 --> 00:29:47.000
I'm detaching and attaching the Ethernet.

00:29:47.120 --> 00:29:50.140
I'm unplugging and
plugging my USB printer,

00:29:50.140 --> 00:29:53.000
and that's the reason I have
to restart my machine,

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:55.940
because it doesn't realize that
it's an adapting environment,

00:29:55.940 --> 00:29:58.060
and eventually,
it just kind of craps out,

00:29:58.060 --> 00:30:01.540
and my machine has to be rebooted,
because I can't print anymore,

00:30:01.540 --> 00:30:04.280
because this driver hasn't adapted
to the fact that I'm going to be

00:30:04.280 --> 00:30:05.710
unplugging and plugging constantly.

00:30:05.720 --> 00:30:08.260
If you're developing
software for the platform,

00:30:08.620 --> 00:30:10.880
understand it's a highly
adaptive platform,

00:30:10.880 --> 00:30:13.460
and therefore,
your app needs to be highly adaptive,

00:30:13.500 --> 00:30:16.020
too, and I'm sure you can all
identify products you've

00:30:16.020 --> 00:30:18.400
used that are not adaptive.

00:30:19.560 --> 00:30:22.160
Another key element of
Mac OS X is multiple users.

00:30:22.250 --> 00:30:23.840
This is true multi-user stuff.

00:30:23.910 --> 00:30:26.270
It's not,
for those of you who came from Mac OS 9,

00:30:26.270 --> 00:30:28.500
it's not pseudo multi-user environment.

00:30:28.500 --> 00:30:32.460
Mac OS X is a truly multi-user system,
and there's some implications for you,

00:30:32.460 --> 00:30:34.420
the app developer, because of that.

00:30:36.130 --> 00:30:38.380
If you have shared resources,
shared blocks of memory,

00:30:38.380 --> 00:30:41.300
or what have you, understand that-- well,
first of all,

00:30:41.300 --> 00:30:44.300
if you allocate memory and you expect
that if you have multiple instances

00:30:44.310 --> 00:30:47.200
of your app running that they're going
to use that shared block of memory,

00:30:47.240 --> 00:30:49.760
then you can use a little
trick called identifying

00:30:49.760 --> 00:30:50.860
those blocks with session IDs.

00:30:51.010 --> 00:30:53.100
But understand,
because of multi-user environment

00:30:53.100 --> 00:30:56.240
and fast user switching,
a user could launch

00:30:56.380 --> 00:30:58.100
your app in one session.

00:30:58.440 --> 00:31:00.840
Somebody else could come along and say,
oh, hey, can I just borrow the

00:31:00.840 --> 00:31:01.860
machine for a second?

00:31:01.860 --> 00:31:03.720
Or, you know, can I borrow the machine?

00:31:03.780 --> 00:31:05.180
Get on it,
switch out to their environment,

00:31:05.180 --> 00:31:06.340
and launch your app as well.

00:31:06.340 --> 00:31:08.460
So now you've got two
instances of your app running.

00:31:08.500 --> 00:31:10.840
What are you going to do with
some of those shared resources?

00:31:10.930 --> 00:31:12.400
And can your app handle that?

00:31:12.460 --> 00:31:15.130
Can it run in multiple contexts?

00:31:15.360 --> 00:31:18.300
Don't assume exclusive
access to resources.

00:31:18.350 --> 00:31:20.640
You might be running
in multiple contexts.

00:31:20.700 --> 00:31:23.960
If your app is using the
iSight camera right now,

00:31:23.990 --> 00:31:27.900
and another user comes along and swaps
out fast user switches to their account,

00:31:28.070 --> 00:31:32.080
you need to give up that camera
so that if they're using iChat,

00:31:32.140 --> 00:31:35.260
or some other software that needs
the camera or some other resource,

00:31:35.320 --> 00:31:36.580
that that's freed up.

00:31:36.630 --> 00:31:38.980
Don't lock it and hold it so
that nobody else can use it

00:31:38.980 --> 00:31:41.210
in any other user context.

00:31:41.810 --> 00:31:43.760
Not all users have the
same access privileges.

00:31:43.890 --> 00:31:46.520
So in one context,
if your app is making some assumptions

00:31:46.520 --> 00:31:50.480
about privileges on the hard drive,
it can't necessarily make the

00:31:50.480 --> 00:31:53.300
same assumptions in the other
context in which it's running.

00:31:53.300 --> 00:31:56.730
Not all users can write to
the applications directory.

00:31:58.770 --> 00:32:01.730
Multiple users,
if your app is running and users save,

00:32:01.740 --> 00:32:02.900
default to their home directory.

00:32:02.900 --> 00:32:04.800
And while I'm talking
about home directories,

00:32:04.870 --> 00:32:07.410
let me just make a point here
that the documents folder

00:32:07.410 --> 00:32:10.620
is only for user-created,
double-clickable documents.

00:32:10.650 --> 00:32:13.480
Don't stick anything in the
documents folder that relates to

00:32:13.480 --> 00:32:15.570
supporting application support files.

00:32:18.900 --> 00:32:25.300
Fast user switching introduces or brings
to light an interesting user experience,

00:32:25.430 --> 00:32:29.520
which is I might be working currently
on the machine in a bunch of software,

00:32:29.520 --> 00:32:32.100
and I'm editing a bunch of documents,
and I didn't save them yet,

00:32:32.190 --> 00:32:33.880
because that's how a lot of people work,
actually.

00:32:33.880 --> 00:32:35.940
And someone comes along to that machine.

00:32:35.940 --> 00:32:38.870
Think of the classroom,
context of a classroom or

00:32:38.880 --> 00:32:40.910
higher ed or even in an office.

00:32:40.920 --> 00:32:43.440
Multiple users using the single machine.

00:32:43.440 --> 00:32:45.530
Current user is editing stuff.

00:32:46.660 --> 00:32:48.710
Another user comes along,
switches out to their,

00:32:48.710 --> 00:32:51.810
logs into their account,
so these files aren't saved, right,

00:32:51.810 --> 00:32:53.980
because the context is just switched out.

00:32:54.130 --> 00:32:56.300
And now the second user
shuts down the machine.

00:32:58.450 --> 00:33:02.080
Well, your app can do some basic stuff
to deal with that and really

00:33:02.090 --> 00:33:03.520
create a great user experience.

00:33:03.600 --> 00:33:05.560
And the Mail app does this today.

00:33:05.560 --> 00:33:09.260
Basically,
it's called Fast Logout and Auto Save.

00:33:09.260 --> 00:33:12.550
As long as your app handles
the standard quit Apple event,

00:33:12.600 --> 00:33:15.620
you're going to get notification
that the machine is going down

00:33:15.620 --> 00:33:17.220
or that your app has to quit,
basically.

00:33:17.220 --> 00:33:20.490
And at that time,
make sure that your app can deal

00:33:20.490 --> 00:33:24.300
with saving a file to a temporary
location provided by the system

00:33:24.300 --> 00:33:26.350
without any user interaction.

00:33:26.780 --> 00:33:29.400
So just assign it some name,
untitled or what have you,

00:33:29.400 --> 00:33:31.810
put it to the temporary
location as a draft,

00:33:31.900 --> 00:33:34.280
and then when your app
restarts next time,

00:33:34.280 --> 00:33:37.760
check that temporary location for
any files that are of your type and

00:33:37.840 --> 00:33:39.230
open those things up automatically.

00:33:39.240 --> 00:33:40.540
Try it with Mail.

00:33:40.540 --> 00:33:42.320
It does a great thing.

00:33:42.320 --> 00:33:44.500
You're drafting some emails, boom,
the system goes down.

00:33:44.500 --> 00:33:46.560
Next time you launch Mail,
those windows open up.

00:33:46.660 --> 00:33:47.670
How cool is that?

00:33:47.740 --> 00:33:50.650
Every app on the platform
should be doing that.

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:55.320
Another thing about the
Mac OS X environment is that it provides

00:33:55.320 --> 00:33:57.370
consistent interface for common tasks.

00:33:57.560 --> 00:34:02.550
The beauty of common interfaces is that
users have the experience of picking

00:34:02.550 --> 00:34:07.690
people or fonts or whatever they're
interacting with from other applications,

00:34:07.690 --> 00:34:10.370
and so they bring that experience
to bear in your application.

00:34:10.400 --> 00:34:13.980
If your app then allows them to pick
fonts or choose colors in a completely

00:34:14.160 --> 00:34:17.510
different way that's custom for your app,
the user has a problem.

00:34:18.860 --> 00:34:21.870
So I think just using all of the
APIs that are available in Mac OS X for

00:34:21.910 --> 00:34:23.560
common interfaces is just great.

00:34:23.560 --> 00:34:24.340
It's just good.

00:34:24.350 --> 00:34:25.630
It's a good thing to do.

00:34:25.660 --> 00:34:27.950
Some examples here,
Address Book Framework,

00:34:27.950 --> 00:34:30.280
Disk Recording for
standardized UI for that,

00:34:30.280 --> 00:34:32.470
Apple Help for user assistance,
and many more.

00:34:32.470 --> 00:34:33.890
I didn't even list half of them here.

00:34:36.630 --> 00:34:40.620
Yet another fundamental and essential
on Mac OS X for every application on

00:34:40.620 --> 00:34:44.900
the platform is the accessibility and
spoken interface feature of Mac OS X.

00:34:44.900 --> 00:34:48.480
Spoken interface today is
in a public or beta preview.

00:34:48.480 --> 00:34:51.100
It's going to be shipped and
built into Mac OS X Tiger.

00:34:51.100 --> 00:34:54.340
If your application,
if your product is shipping

00:34:54.340 --> 00:34:57.590
into education at any
level or into government,

00:34:57.650 --> 00:35:02.150
you need to understand that
Section 508 is a big deal.

00:35:02.160 --> 00:35:04.780
Most customers aren't going to
be purchasing software that's

00:35:04.780 --> 00:35:07.280
not Section 508 compliant,
and there's stuff you can

00:35:07.380 --> 00:35:11.660
do today to prepare for this
capability coming in the future.

00:35:11.660 --> 00:35:14.000
It's actually a lot of this
is in Mac OS X Panther today.

00:35:16.130 --> 00:35:19.100
The accessibility stuff in Spoken
Interface was designed for users who

00:35:19.100 --> 00:35:22.210
are blind or have low vision or other
vision disabilities and other learning

00:35:22.210 --> 00:35:25.270
disabilities or learning disabilities.

00:35:25.490 --> 00:35:27.520
It's built in, not bolted on.

00:35:27.520 --> 00:35:30.900
There's no extra installer,
no licensing to be done from you.

00:35:30.990 --> 00:35:32.610
It works the same way
in every application.

00:35:32.720 --> 00:35:35.450
It leverages the keyboard shortcuts
that you have in your app.

00:35:35.530 --> 00:35:37.570
It just works with
everything that you've done,

00:35:37.740 --> 00:35:39.020
provided you follow the rules.

00:35:39.030 --> 00:35:42.000
And there are rules for how to develop
accessible applications for Carbon,

00:35:42.120 --> 00:35:42.980
Cocoa, and Java.

00:35:42.980 --> 00:35:46.320
Every developer can do this,
and the experience is basically

00:35:46.720 --> 00:35:49.560
that everybody can participate
and use your product,

00:35:49.570 --> 00:35:50.690
all inclusive.

