00:49:20.870 --> 00:49:27.590
Now, designing a good interface requires
that you follow those principles,

00:49:27.590 --> 00:49:29.500
but also think about getting organized.

00:49:29.560 --> 00:49:31.520
And by getting organized,
I'm going to talk about something

00:49:31.520 --> 00:49:34.840
called the user's mental model
or their conceptual model.

00:49:36.030 --> 00:49:38.020
What I mean by that is
that it's important,

00:49:38.020 --> 00:49:40.840
as you understand your markets and
your users and what your feature is

00:49:40.920 --> 00:49:43.200
going to do and the solution it's
going to provide to your users,

00:49:43.200 --> 00:49:44.850
it's important that you
start to think about,

00:49:44.860 --> 00:49:50.660
now, what is the user's conceptual model
or mental model as they approach the

00:49:50.810 --> 00:49:52.880
task that your software is providing?

00:49:52.880 --> 00:49:55.300
What are the concepts
they're thinking about?

00:49:55.300 --> 00:49:57.260
What's the workflow that
they're experiencing?

00:49:57.360 --> 00:50:00.270
What workflow have they experienced?

00:50:00.300 --> 00:50:03.490
What objects and object
hierarchy exist in your product?

00:50:04.790 --> 00:50:08.280
What expectations is the
user bringing to the table?

00:50:09.180 --> 00:50:11.030
These are big questions to ask.

00:50:11.080 --> 00:50:13.980
And a lot of developers that
I've interacted with haven't

00:50:13.980 --> 00:50:14.890
even thought about this stuff.

00:50:14.980 --> 00:50:17.360
They've kind of just, you know,
their impression of what the software

00:50:17.360 --> 00:50:19.020
should do and they've put it together.

00:50:19.020 --> 00:50:21.800
And while it's compelling,
it's not nearly as compelling

00:50:21.800 --> 00:50:23.480
and doesn't register,
I think, with a lot of users.

00:50:23.480 --> 00:50:26.920
This is a really important
concept to get down.

00:50:26.920 --> 00:50:29.930
Once you've figured out
what that conceptual model

00:50:29.930 --> 00:50:33.460
is for 80% of your users,
it's important to reflect that model

00:50:33.460 --> 00:50:36.980
through the menu organization and layout
and organization of the main window,

00:50:36.980 --> 00:50:38.840
toolbars, utility windows, et cetera.

00:50:38.920 --> 00:50:41.160
We'll go through a couple of examples.

00:50:41.780 --> 00:50:45.640
And when you design your product
to reflect that conceptual model,

00:50:45.640 --> 00:50:48.640
it's important to keep these kind
of five points in your mind as well.

00:50:48.640 --> 00:50:51.600
Make sure that there are affordances.

00:50:51.600 --> 00:50:54.640
If something doesn't look clickable,
users won't necessarily know that it is.

00:50:54.720 --> 00:50:56.570
Design for simplicity.

00:50:56.630 --> 00:50:58.090
Keep simplicity in mind.

00:50:58.100 --> 00:51:00.960
Frequently accessed items
should always be accessible.

00:51:00.960 --> 00:51:03.960
Some of the best software
that I've ever used,

00:51:04.060 --> 00:51:07.400
just instantly the stuff I needed
was right there when I needed it.

00:51:07.480 --> 00:51:09.400
And some of the products that
won the Apple Design Awards that

00:51:09.400 --> 00:51:12.260
you'll hear about tonight really
reflect that concept well.

00:51:12.260 --> 00:51:13.890
Familiarity.

00:51:13.900 --> 00:51:17.240
People's mental model is based
on their previous experience.

00:51:17.240 --> 00:51:20.550
We talked earlier about leveraging
the existing UI that's delivered

00:51:20.750 --> 00:51:22.640
through some of the APIs in Mac OS X.

00:51:22.640 --> 00:51:24.710
Take advantage of that
because it provides for a

00:51:24.710 --> 00:51:26.280
familiar experience for users.

00:51:26.280 --> 00:51:27.980
Availability.

00:51:27.980 --> 00:51:31.230
It's a whole lot easier for people
to see something on screen that they

00:51:31.230 --> 00:51:34.910
need to interact with than for them
to recall some menu command that's two

00:51:34.910 --> 00:51:37.200
levels deep or some button in a dialog.

00:51:37.480 --> 00:51:41.880
So expose the features that are critical
to users so that stuff is available.

00:51:41.880 --> 00:51:44.150
And provide good feedback to users,
and we'll talk about

00:51:44.150 --> 00:51:45.310
that more specifically.

00:51:49.450 --> 00:51:52.970
So, how does that apply in the real
world in terms of the design that

00:51:52.970 --> 00:51:54.600
we've implemented for some software?

00:51:54.600 --> 00:51:57.730
Well,
if you think of iTunes and consider the

00:51:57.840 --> 00:52:03.030
mental model or conceptual model that
most users have as they approach this,

00:52:03.220 --> 00:52:08.000
they understand that it's a music
management piece of software.

00:52:08.000 --> 00:52:08.760
It manages their music.

00:52:08.760 --> 00:52:11.980
And so they have an understanding that
there's going to be songs in there.

00:52:12.270 --> 00:52:14.680
There's going to be some way
of organizing those songs.

00:52:14.680 --> 00:52:17.330
They probably have this idea
that you could play the stuff,

00:52:17.330 --> 00:52:19.050
and then maybe they're searching.

00:52:19.300 --> 00:52:21.630
And so the UI is modeled
completely around that.

00:52:21.730 --> 00:52:23.480
There's songs.

00:52:23.490 --> 00:52:26.220
It's a dominant part of the UI.

00:52:27.820 --> 00:52:30.390
There's the collections where we
organize the music into playlists,

00:52:30.450 --> 00:52:31.330
smart playlists, etc.

00:52:31.400 --> 00:52:36.880
There's the playback controls, right,
very clearly on the interface.

00:52:36.940 --> 00:52:39.740
And lastly,
there's the searching functionality.

00:52:39.740 --> 00:52:40.850
It's all there.

00:52:40.870 --> 00:52:44.460
So the UI reflects completely,
or almost perfectly,

00:52:44.460 --> 00:52:46.730
the mental model that users
have as they approach the task.

00:52:46.780 --> 00:52:49.960
And so users just get up and running
with this product really fast.

00:52:50.050 --> 00:52:50.850
They just get it.

00:52:50.940 --> 00:52:52.500
That's what getting it means.

00:52:55.370 --> 00:52:55.980
Next example.

00:52:55.980 --> 00:53:00.030
This is a product called
Unison from Panic.

00:53:00.120 --> 00:53:01.780
These guys do great stuff.

00:53:02.690 --> 00:53:05.880
This is a product that totally revives
the Usenet for Macintosh users.

00:53:05.880 --> 00:53:08.500
Now the Usenet's got lots of content,
and we'll not talk about

00:53:08.500 --> 00:53:11.380
any of that specifically,
but there's some good stuff out there.

00:53:11.380 --> 00:53:14.750
And the mental model that
you approach Usenet with,

00:53:14.750 --> 00:53:18.870
if you know what it is,
you understand what its hierarchy is.

00:53:18.970 --> 00:53:21.510
There's groups and there's
messages within groups,

00:53:21.510 --> 00:53:23.940
and messages contain
pictures and other stuff.

00:53:24.020 --> 00:53:27.300
If you don't know what
Usenet's structure is,

00:53:27.410 --> 00:53:30.450
Unison's product is so,
Unison is so well designed in

00:53:30.450 --> 00:53:34.110
terms of the mental model that
it basically communicates the

00:53:34.110 --> 00:53:37.490
model of the environment to you,
the user, and so you get it right away.

00:53:37.500 --> 00:53:40.000
And so here,
basically Usenet is all about groups,

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:43.030
and so the main groups window is
structured in a way that you just

00:53:43.030 --> 00:53:45.040
kind of go through the browser view.

00:53:46.720 --> 00:53:50.700
And there's a menu that
supports that key concept.

00:53:50.780 --> 00:53:54.370
And then within a message,
we've got the four elements of message,

00:53:54.460 --> 00:53:55.930
files, images, music.

00:53:56.150 --> 00:53:59.790
And so there's a message
menu that is part of this.

00:53:59.890 --> 00:54:03.350
So the UI really supports
the model that exists.

00:54:05.520 --> 00:54:07.990
Soft RAID,
another great product in Mac OS X.

00:54:07.990 --> 00:54:17.550
If you're doing RAID stuff,
you basically have a simple mental model,

00:54:17.550 --> 00:54:17.550
which is you've got physical devices,

00:54:18.230 --> 00:54:23.560
Which it calls "Discs." You've
got logical volumes on those

00:54:23.640 --> 00:54:28.590
discs called-- You've got
logical volumes called "Volumes."

00:54:29.070 --> 00:54:30.860
And there's a menu to support that,
sorry.

00:54:30.980 --> 00:54:34.500
And then there's a utilities menu,
which I don't highlight.

00:54:34.630 --> 00:54:35.860
Sorry, I run through these slides again.

00:54:35.920 --> 00:54:37.280
There's a utilities menu,
which basically is,

00:54:37.280 --> 00:54:38.760
you've got these hard disks,
you've got these volumes,

00:54:38.780 --> 00:54:43.060
and then you do some utilitarian stuff
to these drives or these volumes,

00:54:43.060 --> 00:54:44.800
and you format them,
or you partition them, or what have you.

00:54:45.060 --> 00:54:46.760
And that's it, that's the UI.

00:54:46.820 --> 00:54:50.240
And yet it's a highly complex,
highly functional product.

00:54:50.250 --> 00:54:52.200
It does a ton of stuff,
but most of it is hidden

00:54:52.200 --> 00:54:55.510
behind the scenes for you,
the user, because you don't need

00:54:55.510 --> 00:54:56.960
to be concerned with it.

00:54:57.400 --> 00:54:58.770
Another great product, Bike Route.

00:54:58.780 --> 00:55:01.610
If you're a cyclist,
this is a really cool product.

00:55:01.720 --> 00:55:05.090
It basically lets you download,
take map formats,

00:55:05.090 --> 00:55:09.850
there's a certain map format out there,
I can't remember the exact details,

00:55:09.850 --> 00:55:13.880
but there's maps out there about cycling,
biking paths or routes

00:55:13.880 --> 00:55:15.700
that exist in the world.

00:55:15.700 --> 00:55:18.860
And you can load those maps
into the product and then come

00:55:18.860 --> 00:55:20.470
up with custom bike trips.

00:55:20.580 --> 00:55:24.960
And you choose different nodes
and then it's got this concept

00:55:24.960 --> 00:55:26.920
of a map but then a route.

00:55:27.370 --> 00:55:30.090
And then within a route you've
got the profile of that route,

00:55:30.090 --> 00:55:33.390
which is the altitudes you might
cycle around and what the instructions

00:55:33.390 --> 00:55:35.420
are for following that custom thing.

00:55:35.420 --> 00:55:37.990
Anyway,
the point is the UI totally supports

00:55:38.070 --> 00:55:41.040
this model that you come to,
which is that I've got a map

00:55:41.100 --> 00:55:42.800
and it's got routes on it.

00:55:46.090 --> 00:55:48.120
And so the route could just
be between those two points,

00:55:48.150 --> 00:55:50.320
and there's a menu associated with that,
and that's it.

00:55:50.320 --> 00:55:54.500
And so the mental model the user comes to
this product with is supported by the UI,

00:55:54.500 --> 00:56:00.390
and the hierarchy of objects and such
is set up in the main menu bar as well.

00:56:01.580 --> 00:56:02.820
But it isn't always that easy.

00:56:02.890 --> 00:56:04.460
It's easy to get this wrong.

00:56:04.460 --> 00:56:08.820
Here's a great product,
and this is in no way meant to

00:56:08.820 --> 00:56:11.100
belittle the product in any way,
shape, or form.

00:56:11.100 --> 00:56:11.750
Mac Journal.

00:56:11.750 --> 00:56:13.500
It won an Apple Design Award years ago.

00:56:13.500 --> 00:56:14.930
I think this is a really cool product.

00:56:14.940 --> 00:56:17.860
But there's one little
thing that I think is wrong.

00:56:17.860 --> 00:56:20.050
And that is that as
I approach this product,

00:56:20.050 --> 00:56:23.640
and as most users approach the product,
they have this concept of a journal,

00:56:23.640 --> 00:56:25.720
which is kind of the container object,
right?

00:56:25.720 --> 00:56:27.890
And within a journal, you've got entries.

00:56:28.510 --> 00:56:31.520
Well, the hierarchy of the main menu
bar doesn't reflect that at all.

00:56:31.520 --> 00:56:36.900
In fact, if you think about app menu,
document menu, right, file menu, edit,

00:56:36.900 --> 00:56:39.180
and then other stuff,
which is where you kind

00:56:39.180 --> 00:56:42.280
of go parent object,
child object, sub-child object,

00:56:42.280 --> 00:56:43.870
et cetera,
that's the hierarchy you should

00:56:43.870 --> 00:56:44.800
be reflecting in the menu bar.

00:56:44.800 --> 00:56:46.340
That's not reflected here.

00:56:46.340 --> 00:56:49.500
So the journal,
which is the parent container object,

00:56:49.500 --> 00:56:51.960
is actually further down
the menu bar than the entry.

00:56:54.230 --> 00:56:57.220
itself, because journals contain entries,
entry is really in the

00:56:57.220 --> 00:56:58.420
place of the document.

00:56:58.420 --> 00:57:03.080
And I just -- personally,
I think that's backwards.

00:57:03.080 --> 00:57:05.290
So the change, I would say,
is just flip those around.

00:57:05.420 --> 00:57:07.970
They call -- the window is
called the Journal Window.

00:57:07.970 --> 00:57:09.970
It's actually the document format,
et cetera.

00:57:10.080 --> 00:57:13.500
And so I hope this drives home the
point that the menu bar needs to

00:57:13.640 --> 00:57:15.600
reflect the hierarchy of your objects.

00:57:15.650 --> 00:57:16.560
Let's take another example.

00:57:16.650 --> 00:57:18.840
If you're a multimedia
authoring application,

00:57:19.030 --> 00:57:22.460
you probably have your document format,
which is your project.

00:57:22.670 --> 00:57:24.900
Within projects, you've got a background.

00:57:24.900 --> 00:57:26.470
Well, you might have scenes.

00:57:26.570 --> 00:57:28.940
Scenes have backgrounds.

00:57:28.940 --> 00:57:30.720
Scenes also have layers.

00:57:30.720 --> 00:57:34.130
Layers have, you know,
characters or objects.

00:57:34.200 --> 00:57:35.880
Objects have attributes.

00:57:35.960 --> 00:57:38.780
And so you could imagine
the menu bar going,

00:57:38.780 --> 00:57:44.900
you know, app name, projects, edit,
scenes, you know, characters, format,

00:57:44.900 --> 00:57:47.720
you know, for attributes, et cetera.

00:57:47.830 --> 00:57:50.960
And so your menu bar needs to reflect
that hierarchy from parent down

00:57:50.960 --> 00:57:55.660
to the -- to the to the smallest
child sort of container element.

00:57:57.010 --> 00:57:59.000
And if you don't get the
mental model right at all,

00:57:59.000 --> 00:58:01.600
basically you go back to what
I was talking about earlier in the

00:58:01.600 --> 00:58:04.660
Knowing Your Application slide,
which is you get just feature creep.

00:58:04.930 --> 00:58:07.640
Your product is all about
features rather than a solution.

00:58:07.640 --> 00:58:11.470
Here's a product that is supposed
to be a to-do list manager,

00:58:11.470 --> 00:58:15.220
but it's so laden with features
and buttons in the toolbar,

00:58:15.220 --> 00:58:19.580
and I didn't even show the menu bar,
I don't even know where to begin.

00:58:19.610 --> 00:58:23.460
I don't know what the model is
that this application works on.

00:58:23.460 --> 00:58:25.820
And so it becomes a problem.

00:58:25.820 --> 00:58:28.430
The feature, while it's a very,
very capable product,

00:58:28.430 --> 00:58:31.280
and I'll just side note,
I'm working with this developer

00:58:31.340 --> 00:58:34.780
to make this thing pretty cool,
but I wanted to show an

00:58:34.780 --> 00:58:38.310
earlier instance of this window
because it's just messed up,

00:58:38.410 --> 00:58:40.860
and you have no idea what
you're supposed to do.

00:58:40.860 --> 00:58:44.480
A to-do list manager product, to me,
should be very lightweight,

00:58:44.620 --> 00:58:48.080
not in my face, be there when I need it,
and then go away when I don't need it,

00:58:48.080 --> 00:58:50.460
and all that kind of stuff,
and this app doesn't do that.

00:58:50.550 --> 00:58:52.670
I can't size the window
beyond a certain small size,

00:58:52.670 --> 00:58:56.290
which basically takes up my whole screen,
and there's too much stuff all over it.

00:58:56.860 --> 00:59:00.000
So, all right,
another element of designing

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:04.200
a great interface is providing
great feedback and communication.

00:59:05.850 --> 00:59:11.080
You know, this is, in my opinion,
providing good feedback to your

00:59:11.080 --> 00:59:14.710
users is like the feedback and
communication we need to have in

00:59:14.760 --> 00:59:17.980
good relationships in our life,
whether it's to our bosses

00:59:17.980 --> 00:59:21.300
or our teammates or spouses
or children or what have you.

00:59:21.300 --> 00:59:23.500
I think there's a great parallel
that can be drawn there.

00:59:23.500 --> 00:59:27.800
And if you think about the feedback
that you provide in your application,

00:59:27.830 --> 00:59:32.350
how you report errors or how you give
status updates or communicate progress,

00:59:32.350 --> 00:59:35.670
it may not be so non-intrusive,
non-interruptive.

00:59:35.800 --> 00:59:35.800
You know,
this is a must for anyone involved

00:59:35.800 --> 00:59:35.800
in developing a Mac OS X product.

00:59:35.800 --> 00:59:35.800
And if you think about the feedback
that you provide in your application,

00:59:35.800 --> 00:59:35.800
how you report errors or how you give
status updates or communicate progress,

00:59:35.800 --> 00:59:35.860
it may not be so non-intrusive,
non-interruptive.

