You know,
this is a must for anyone involved

00:59:35.860 --> 00:59:35.860
in developing a Mac OS X product.

00:59:35.860 --> 00:59:35.860
And if you think about the feedback
that you provide in your application,

00:59:35.860 --> 00:59:35.860
how you report errors or how you give
status updates or communicate progress,

00:59:35.860 --> 00:59:35.860
it may not be so non-intrusive,
non-interruptive.

01:00:05.800 --> 01:00:06.800
in your application.

01:00:06.800 --> 01:00:09.960
You want to figure out what
are the reporting points?

01:00:10.080 --> 01:00:12.800
What are those milestones that the
user really wants to know about?

01:00:12.800 --> 01:00:15.370
And then how do we effectively
communicate the reaching of

01:00:15.470 --> 01:00:17.870
those milestones or the not
reaching of those milestones?

01:00:17.920 --> 01:00:20.140
So only communicate status that matters.

01:00:20.140 --> 01:00:22.240
Use appropriate progress indication.

01:00:22.240 --> 01:00:25.300
So either an indeterminate bar
or a determinate progress bar

01:00:25.300 --> 01:00:26.700
or the spinning gear thing.

01:00:26.900 --> 01:00:31.940
And related to that,
I think consistent placement of those

01:00:31.940 --> 01:00:35.780
little gauges or dials or whatever
you're using to communicate status.

01:00:35.780 --> 01:00:38.240
It should be consistent placement.

01:00:38.240 --> 01:00:42.160
If you look at mail, the spinning gear is
always in the same place.

01:00:42.260 --> 01:00:45.920
And users get accustomed to looking
in that location for an update as

01:00:45.920 --> 01:00:49.630
to whether or not the machine is
busy or the application is busy.

01:00:49.640 --> 01:00:53.670
Consistent placement
of progress indicators.

01:00:53.670 --> 01:00:57.820
Another way of communicating feedback
is through badging your dock icon.

01:00:57.820 --> 01:01:00.690
You can, like mail does,
you can show the number of

01:01:00.690 --> 01:01:02.600
mail messages that are there.

01:01:02.600 --> 01:01:05.750
And other apps are doing some really
cool stuff with their application icons.

01:01:05.760 --> 01:01:10.080
And then providing users with useful
error messages and disabling commands

01:01:10.080 --> 01:01:12.560
that don't apply in the current context.

01:01:12.650 --> 01:01:14.810
I want to zero in on these
because I still see a lot

01:01:14.810 --> 01:01:16.270
of difficulty in this area.

01:01:16.280 --> 01:01:21.180
So it's important to report errors,
but not this way.

01:01:21.180 --> 01:01:24.650
And this is out of a
shipping app on the platform.

01:01:26.290 --> 01:01:28.970
It's important to report errors,
but always check spelling.

01:01:28.970 --> 01:01:31.800
So this says, in case you can't read
at the back of the room,

01:01:31.800 --> 01:01:32.880
it says, aim error.

01:01:32.880 --> 01:01:36.310
Could not add mformic at mac.com,
guy on my team, to your buddy list.

01:01:36.610 --> 01:01:37.950
Feedback error is zero.

01:01:37.950 --> 01:01:40.820
I'm not sure what a feedback error is.

01:01:46.060 --> 01:01:51.200
It's important to report errors or
report a situation that's occurred.

01:01:51.200 --> 01:01:55.340
It might not necessarily be an error,
but it's something that's occurred that

01:01:55.340 --> 01:01:58.040
hinders you from proceeding further.

01:01:58.040 --> 01:02:00.670
Here's an app that I was
playing with the other day,

01:02:00.670 --> 01:02:03.870
and it requires that you drag
and drop an image onto each side,

01:02:03.880 --> 01:02:06.700
into these kind of giant
image wells or whatever.

01:02:06.700 --> 01:02:09.310
And so I dragged an
image in out of iPhoto,

01:02:09.310 --> 01:02:10.760
and that was great.

01:02:10.760 --> 01:02:14.150
And then I dragged another image,
which happened to be oriented

01:02:14.150 --> 01:02:15.850
differently than the first.

01:02:15.970 --> 01:02:18.170
The one was portrait,
and the other one came in at landscape.

01:02:18.170 --> 01:02:19.060
And I didn't know.

01:02:19.060 --> 01:02:21.300
There was no indication in the
UI that I couldn't do that.

01:02:21.670 --> 01:02:25.700
And so I did that,
and I got this sheet came down,

01:02:25.820 --> 01:02:28.840
and it said,
drag the image as a different size,

01:02:29.050 --> 01:02:29.830
extend or crop.

01:02:34.930 --> 01:02:38.820
Well, I just dragged an image in here.

01:02:38.840 --> 01:02:40.180
I don't want to extend or crop it.

01:02:40.230 --> 01:02:43.100
And I'm not sure where distort came from,
actually.

01:02:45.980 --> 01:02:51.340
At this point, I'm thinking, OK,
but I can't cancel.

01:02:51.430 --> 01:02:52.860
So now what's going to happen?

01:02:52.930 --> 01:02:54.620
Now, in this case, it's not a big deal.

01:02:54.640 --> 01:02:55.140
But you know what?

01:02:55.140 --> 01:03:02.590
If this was some crazy 3D
rendering task that I just

01:03:02.600 --> 01:03:05.500
started and I couldn't cancel,
I'd be screwed.

01:03:05.500 --> 01:03:08.310
Because this thing would go
off for a period of time,

01:03:08.310 --> 01:03:11.580
and I'd be stuck because I couldn't
stop the thing from processing,

01:03:11.580 --> 01:03:13.390
doing whatever it's doing.

