So I'm not sure what I'm
supposed to do with this message.

01:03:15.700 --> 01:03:18.310
It doesn't communicate enough.

01:03:20.100 --> 01:03:21.820
I don't know where distort came from.

01:03:21.820 --> 01:03:28.730
It's important to report problems
effectively and provide users

01:03:28.730 --> 01:03:29.720
with useful error messages.

01:03:29.720 --> 01:03:32.240
I've talked about this every year,
and I feel compelled

01:03:32.790 --> 01:03:34.510
to talk about it again.

01:03:34.520 --> 01:03:36.240
I apologize if you were here before.

01:03:36.240 --> 01:03:39.680
What happened is what you
should say to the user,

01:03:39.680 --> 01:03:42.880
then tell them why it happened,
and then tell them what

01:03:42.880 --> 01:03:43.760
they can do about it.

01:03:43.860 --> 01:03:45.310
What's the solution to the problem?

01:03:45.320 --> 01:03:47.750
Avoid yes and no buttons.

01:03:47.760 --> 01:03:49.280
There's a lot of ambiguity.

01:03:49.560 --> 01:03:53.000
It's often very difficult to write
a good error message and then have a

01:03:53.000 --> 01:03:56.020
yes or no button associated with it,
because the user can't, well,

01:03:56.020 --> 01:03:56.960
we'll talk about why.

01:03:56.960 --> 01:03:59.260
There's that problem,
and then there's the other problem,

01:03:59.260 --> 01:04:02.020
and that is that users tend
to scan the error message,

01:04:02.020 --> 01:04:05.520
looking for kind of keywords, you know,
that indicate the problem,

01:04:05.520 --> 01:04:09.800
and your button labels should
kind of capture those keywords

01:04:09.970 --> 01:04:13.320
as the user scans that message
to know which button to click.

01:04:13.470 --> 01:04:15.010
You know,
there's something about preferences,

01:04:15.010 --> 01:04:17.140
and then there's a button that
says open system preferences.

01:04:17.140 --> 01:04:19.500
So you just kind of go, whoop,
hit the button.

01:04:19.500 --> 01:04:23.200
and boom,
they're off to solving the problem.

01:04:23.380 --> 01:04:25.210
And then, of course,
you could prevent problems from occurring

01:04:25.210 --> 01:04:28.420
in the first place by just disabling
menu commands or buttons that don't

01:04:28.420 --> 01:04:31.500
make any sense in the current context,
but heaven forbid that that

01:04:31.500 --> 01:04:33.220
would happen sometimes.

01:04:33.370 --> 01:04:37.780
So here's a way of reporting an error,
you know, error writing file to disk.

01:04:37.920 --> 01:04:38.860
Well, it's a good sentence.

01:04:38.860 --> 01:04:39.840
It's a complete sentence.

01:04:39.840 --> 01:04:41.960
Everything is there that you need
to have there to be good English,

01:04:41.960 --> 01:04:44.440
but it's a little, you know,
it's not too outgoing.

01:04:44.440 --> 01:04:48.180
So a better report would be this one.

01:04:48.180 --> 01:04:50.520
The document cannot be saved
because the disk is full.

01:04:50.520 --> 01:04:52.870
Okay, so now I know a little bit
more about what's going on.

01:04:53.370 --> 01:04:56.140
And I could probably, from this message,
figure out what I need to do,

01:04:56.140 --> 01:04:58.830
which is if I want to save this document,
I've got to go to the finder and

01:04:58.830 --> 01:05:01.670
get rid of something so I get a
little bit more space on the drive.

01:05:01.700 --> 01:05:05.870
But a whole lot better would
be to do something like this.

01:05:06.000 --> 01:05:06.860
And why is this better?

01:05:06.860 --> 01:05:09.360
Because, first of all,
it communicates what happened.

01:05:09.360 --> 01:05:12.030
The document trip request
could not be saved.

01:05:14.230 --> 01:05:14.860
Why did it happen?

01:05:14.860 --> 01:05:16.250
Because the disk works stuff.

01:05:16.390 --> 01:05:19.160
Not only is the disk full,
but it tells me which disk.

01:05:19.180 --> 01:05:23.210
A lot of us have partitioned drives,
multiple hard drives, iDisk, etc.

01:05:23.290 --> 01:05:25.240
And now what do I do about it?

01:05:25.360 --> 01:05:29.690
Try deleting documents from that drive
or saving the document on another disk.

01:05:29.730 --> 01:05:31.790
That's a good error message.

01:05:31.800 --> 01:05:34.340
And I wish I would get this kind
of stuff in all of the applications

01:05:34.340 --> 01:05:35.610
that I run on the platform.

01:05:35.610 --> 01:05:38.190
And it means a little bit of extra
work on your part as a developer,

01:05:38.300 --> 01:05:40.300
as an engineer,
because you've got to start looking

01:05:40.320 --> 01:05:43.220
at some of those error codes that
are coming back from the APIs.

01:05:43.980 --> 01:05:45.690
And that's hard, but you know what?

01:05:45.880 --> 01:05:48.980
The end result is a great,
great experience for customers.

01:05:50.920 --> 01:05:52.330
And again, prevention is the key.

01:05:52.340 --> 01:05:55.120
Rather than display a dialogue
or an alert that's like this,

01:05:55.120 --> 01:05:58.320
that says, "You must select at least one
student "before printing the

01:05:58.430 --> 01:06:00.780
student attendance summary report,"

01:06:01.530 --> 01:06:02.470
Disable the menu items.

01:06:02.570 --> 01:06:04.570
So I can't go up and say print
student summary report if

01:06:04.670 --> 01:06:06.400
there's no student selected,
right?

01:06:06.400 --> 01:06:07.070
It's easy.

01:06:07.070 --> 01:06:09.490
You can do this,
and a lot of apps are doing it,

01:06:09.490 --> 01:06:13.560
and I hope to see this happening in
100% of the apps on the platform.

01:06:13.560 --> 01:06:15.280
So prevent the problem
in the first place,

01:06:15.370 --> 01:06:18.440
then you don't have to look at the
error messages and report the alerts.

